  <hr /><a name="passant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">PASSANT </dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term used when an animal is depicted walking on all four paws, or with one paw raised, and generally towards the dexter � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#trippant">trippant</a>&rsquo;.  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3995.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3995.gif" alt="[passant]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d1075.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d1075.gif" alt="[passant]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4595.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4595.gif" alt="[example of passant]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <em><br>Flag of <a href="nl-wfrij.html#his1">West-Friesland</a> c1720, The Netherlands (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="cz-fm-ks.html">Ko�a&#345;iska</a>, Czechia (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="de-pc-04.html#mz">Marnitz</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
 
  <hr /><a name="passantguardant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">PASSANT GUARDANT (or PASSANT GARDANT)</dt>
